Sentiment Analysis of headlines about US presidents in their first year of mandate¶

This is the final project of the Automated Media Content Analysis module, as part of the program Mannheim Master in Data Science of the University of Mannheim, developed by Souza, V. F. during the winter semester of 2021/22.

1. Introduction¶

With the wide spread of instant messaging apps such as Whatsapp and Telegram, and the frequent restriction of full-article reading by famous journals to subscribers, news' headlines and snippets have become more important in the information sharing dynamic. Headlines are the titles, often in bold and greater size, while snippets are the small text that can be read right below the headlines in instant messaging apps' and social media's pre-visualization. Both texts plus the image that appears when sharing articles are the newspaper's chance of convincing potential readers that the full content is worth a subscription, and are certainly read more frequently than the article's paragraphs.

In order to become interesting and curious, these short texts might carry sentiment, irony, analogies, and even mystery. Their vocabulary must be carefully chosen to make the article at the same time informative and instigating, and it might also reveal the newspaper's position towards some subject. Specifically in the political environment, measuring the sentiment of news' summaries regarding politicians, parties, and agendas are important for understanding its influence in social behavior.

As both media content and text processing techniques have become more easily available in the digital era through websites, API's, and open-source programming languages and packages, automated analysis of media content was also made easier. Huge text corpses that would require hours of repeated human tasks can now be processed in seconds, and using advanced Natural Language Processing (NLP) approaches in programmable techniques. Among the existing NLP tasks, Sentiment Classification has been increasingly used for analytical purposes, as it can classify some text as positive, negative or neutral, extract latent and subjective meaning from it, and therefore make different groups of text comparable objectively.

In this project report, the sentiment of headlines and snippets from The New York Times articles concerning two United States presidents - Donald Trump and Joe Biden - in their first year of government were analyzed to investigate the following research questions:

  • Did the news about the polemic president Donald Trump during 2017 carry more negative sentiment than news about Joe Biden in 2021?
  • Did the average sentiment of these news range during the year, possibly affected by significant occurrences?
  • Does the average sentiment obtained by NLP techniques correlate with approval rates in the same periods?

To answer these questions, more than 7000 New York Time's articles about Trump (2017) and Biden (2021) were scrapped through the journal's official API, and then classified by three different pre-trained models of Sentiment Classification available in Python: Textblob, VADER and Flair. In order to choose the classifier that performed best, a random sample of 1000 articles was annotated twice by 40 different human coders. Both Inter-Annotator Agreement reliability scores Cohen's Kappa and Krippendorff's Alpha were low, and only agreement occurrences were considered as gold standard for validation. The VADER sentiment classifier showed the higher scores for F1 and macro average precision, so its labels were used for the analysis.

2. Literature Review¶

Sentiment Analysis¶

The automated sentiment reasoning of a large or numerous text corpse is a task of interest for different contexts, as it becomes cheaper to infer certain conclusions without the need of reading the entire text (Boukes, 2020). Specially the reasoning of sentiment contained in news' headlines is an important task, as the headline is the first (and sometimes the only) part of an article people actually read, and shapes the context in which people read the article (van Atteveldt, 2021).

Inter-coder Reliability¶

Different measures were proposed to quantify Inter-coder Agreement in classification tasks with 2 or more annotators. One frequently used in double annotations is Cohen's Kappa (1960), which is also implemented in Python's Scikit-learn package. It is calculated by comparing observed agreement ratio, and the expected agreement when both annotators assign labels randomly. Ten years later, Krippendorff (1970) published his Krippendorff's Alpha reliability score for Inter-coder Agreement, which also compares observed versus expected agreement by chance, but in broader use cases (e.g., many annotators, many classes, missing values). He also updated continuously the guidelines for the use of this score (Krippendorff, 2012) and included computational implementations. In Python there is also an implementation of Krippendorff's Alpha available in PyPI. In both cases, it is desired to have a reliability score close to 1 (perfect agreement) and away from 0 (agreement by chance).

3. Method¶

The methodology is divided in the following 4 macro steps, each of them requiring specific preprocessing minor steps, libraries, and evaluations:

  1. Data Acquisition
  2. Human Coding of a Random Sample
  3. Comparison of Sentiment Classifiers
  4. Sentiment Analysis with the Final Labels

They are followed by code blocks that can be re-run in a local environment to obtain the same results. The following Python library versions were used:

3.1. Data Acquisition¶

All the articles used in this project were obtained through New York Time's Article Search API, which required an account creation for allowing the use of an API key. Some parameters from the /articlesearch.json endpoint were used to filter the result and iterate through its pagination, and a 6.5-second-sleep between requests was necessary not to exceed the limit of 10 requests per minute.

First, all the 5288 articles published between January 21st of 2017 and 52 weeks ahead containing the word "Trump" in the headline were retrieved and stored in the file df_nyt_trump.csv, so this code block would not have to run again. The same was made to retrieve the 2157 articles published between January 21st of 2021 and 52 weeks ahead containing "Biden" in their headlines, and then stored in df_nyt_biden.csv.

The endpoint's parameter sort was set to oldest to always retrieve articles in the same chronological order, instead of using the default relevance. Therefore, both datasets would be the same if this code ran in different points of time.

Both Trump's and Biden's datasets were then combined into the Pandas DataFrame variable df, keeping only important columns and filtering only articles published before the end of 2017 and 2021, respectively.

3.2. Human Coding of a Random Sample¶

As the final dataset contains more than 7000 different articles and no gold standard for sentiment was available, a smaller sample of size 1000 was randomly extracted to be used in the validation process of the models. This sample was generated using Scikit-Learn's train_test_split method, with its random_seed set to 42, and the result was stored in the file df_test.csv. The same proportion of articles per president from the original dataset was kept for the sample, using parameter stratify.

These 1000 articles were then randomly divided between 40 human annotators, in such a way that each article was classified by 2 independent annotators as positive, negative or neutral. All annotators received the same instructions, and they could not see each other's classifications.

All these annotations were compiled outside this notebook into the file df_annotations.csv, which was imported to calculate both reliability scores of Inter-Annotator Agreement Cohen's Kappa and Krippendorff's Alpha. Percent agreement was 60.9%, and as the number of annotators is 2, both scores lead to a similar value of 0.36, which is considered low. This might be due to the high subjectivity of this task in a political domain, where the same headline and snippet can cause opposite sentiments and interpretations in different people.

In order to build a reliable reference, only the 609 occurrences of agreement were considered the gold standard for this task and added to the original dataset df as the column sentiment_agreement.

3.3. Comparison of Sentiment Classifiers¶

Three pre-trained Python models of Sentiment Classification with different approaches and complexities were tested to correctly classify the sentiment of the headlines and snippets:

  • TextBlob: Lexicon-based sentiment analyzer with a Bag of Words approach and some predefined rules to consider negation words. For a given text, it returns a polarity score ranging between -1.0 and +1.0, which is an average of the polarities associated with each word. Polarity scores equal 0.0 were considered neutral, while positive scores were considered positive and negative were considered negative.
  • VADER: Short for "Valence Aware Dictionary and sEntiment Reasoner", VADER is also a lexicon and rule-based sentiment analysis tool based mostly on sentiments expressed in social media, but generally applicable to other domains. It was published by Hutto, & Gilbert in 2014, and associates different intensities (valences) for the sentiment of each word of its vocabulary, and has a built-in algorithm to change sentiment intensity based on punctuations, slang, emojis, and acronyms. The same threshold used for TextBlob's polarity score was used for VADER's compound score.
  • Flair: Flair is a state-of-art NLP framework built on PyTorch and a combination of different embeddings to various NLP tasks, published by Akbik et al. (2018). Its sentiment classifier, unlike TextBlob and VADER, classifies texts only between positive and negative, with a confidence score ranging between 0 and 1. In order to include a third class, classifications with confidence score below the threshold of 0.75 were considered neutral.

No text pre-processing was needed because all three implementations are made to deal with raw text strings as input. As this is a multi-class classification task with certain class imbalance (there are more negative articles), accuracy score alone is not the best evaluation metric to compare them. In this sense, macro average precision and F1 score were also used to evaluate the models against the gold standard.

Although Flair achieved the best accuracy (0.61), VADER had the highest macro average precision (0.56) and F1 score (0.50), so the following analysis were made using its labels as sentiment.

3.4. Sentiment Analysis with the Final Labels¶
To compare the sentiment of news between both US presidents in their first year of government and answer the research questions, the following metrics were observed: percentage of positive and negative sentiments, and average sentiment (VADER's compound score, ranging between -1 and +1). These metrics were calculated considering the whole period, and also month by month.


The dataset was divided into four different text corpses (Trump Positive, Trump Negative, Biden Positive and Biden Negative), so that text features from each corpse could be analyzed for deeper understanding using word clouds and filtered sampling. Specifically for this step, the following text pre-processing steps were required to normalize input text:


    

  • Lower case all characters;
    • 

  • Remove punctuations;
    • 

  • Remove English stop words and common irrelevant words;
    • 

  • Lemmatize word variations.
    • 



A word cloud with the most frequent words from each of the four corpses was plotted, so they could be compared. Then certain notable words from this clouds were used to filter samples for context extraction.

Text Pre-processing¶












In [29]:



    


def preprocess(text):
    """
    Apply the following Text Preprocessing steps to the text: 
    Lower key > Remove Punctuation > Tokenize >  
    Remove English Stopwords > Lemmatize 
    """

    text = str.lower(str(text))
    
    punctuations = string.punctuation + ''
    text_p = "".join([char for char in text if char not in punctuations])
    
    words = word_tokenize(text_p)
    
    stop_words = stopwords.words('english') 
    filtered_words = [word for word in words if word not in stop_words]
    
    lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()
    lemmatized = [lemmatizer.lemmatize(word) for word in filtered_words]
    
    return lemmatized

df["headline_snippet_prepr"] = df["headline_snippet"].apply(preprocess)
df[["headline.main", "snippet", "headline_snippet_prepr"]].sample(5)

4. Results and Discussion¶














4.1. Sentiment Statistics¶
As shown by the following table and graphics, Donald Trump accumulated much more negative headlines during 2017 (45%) than his successor Joe Biden during 2021 (36%), while the second accumulated more positive headlines than the first (48% against 39%). It is to be noticed that president Donald Trump was also more polemic, because news about him during his first tenure year in New York Times were double more frequent in all sentiment classes. Considering VADER's compound polarity score, Trump's average sentiment was slightly negative (-0.04), while Biden's was slightly positive (+0.06).


In comparison to approval rates, Trump's rate by the end of his first year was 37.7%, while Biden's achieved 43.1%, according to the portal FiveThirtyEight. However, Biden kept his approval rate more than 10 percentage points above Trump's during most of their first years, and this difference decreased after August of each year. When looking at average sentiment month by month, it is to notice that in August there was a special peak of negative headlines about Biden in 2021, and both presidents reached 55% of negative sentiment and -0.1 of average sentiment.


This might have happened due to the withdrawal of American troops from Afghanistan during August 2021, which led to Taliban militants returning to power in this country. This was certainly the most negative and controversial episode in Biden's first year of government, and might have made his popularity fall to the same level of his predecessor's.

4.2. Word Cloud and Filtered Samples¶
The 4 different word clouds were generated using the Python library WordCloud, which is able to include bigram collocations as a single token in case both words co-occur too frequently.


While looking at the most frequent words in negative and positive headlines about Trump, expressions like "White House", "republican", "leader", "American" and "administration" appear quite often in both cases. Frequent expressions that are more exclusive to negative news are "travel ban", "war", "attack", "threat" and "North Korea", and filtered samples containing such words suggest that the journal used to criticize the former president for his international diplomacy.


In contrast to Trump's word cloud, Biden's positive headlines seem to be more about vaccinating the entire country against Covid-19 with a big investment, as suggested by the frequent expressions "vaccination", "trillion", "million", "pandemic" and "plan". On the other hand, "Afghanistan" and "climate change" are more exclusive of Biden's negative headlines. In case of samples containing "Afghanistan", the president was criticized for his decision of withdrawing American troops, which led to violent episodes and popular frustration. However, headlines containing "climate change" seem to be false negatives, because they carry mostly positive ideas but succeeded by the negative word "fight". This is one of the limitations of lexicon based approaches.

5. Conclusion¶
Despite its low accuracy when faced against the gold standard, VADER classifications can be considered a useful tool for sentiment analysis and a good thermometer for public opinion. Both average sentiment and percentage of positive/negative headlines behaved as expected, considering presidential approval rates as benchmark. This reasoner captured that Donald Trump accumulated more negative sentiment in New York Times headlines during his first mandate year than his successor, but also that Joe Biden faced popularity issues in August 2021.


However, it has limitations as any Lexicon based approach. Words that are generally ranked as negative, can also be used to negate other negative expressions - VADER deals with common negations, like "no" and "not", but cases like "fight climate change" seem to be classified as negative. Such cases would only be captured by more advanced techniques, trained on large labeled datasets of political domain. All pre-trained models tested in this project were mostly built on either social media (mainly Twitter) and/or movie reviews datasets, which might not share exactly the same political vocabulary as a newspaper.


The main suggestions of next steps for similar projects are the use of a larger and more reliable (higher Krippendorff's alpha) dataset to use as gold standard, and training different Deep Learning models on these labels. Word Embeddings, LSTM and transformers might be good candidates for the task, as they are state-of-the-art techniques.
